The two log paths happening per retailer transfer
Path 1: MikAura lifecycle logs (_transfer_info, _transfer_warning, etc.)
These call status_logger.log_info(message, **fields) which internally runs _build_entry() + _emit() to print a flat JSON line:

{"pipeline_context":"Data Ingestion Pipeline","client_name":"madebygather","status":"info","message":"Lambda 2 completed: 3 files, 142 records","files_processed":3,"records_processed":142,"level":"INFO","timestamp":"...","correlation_id":"...","environment":"dev"}
These are operational lifecycle logs -- "Lambda started", "Lambda completed", "file skipped", etc. Their status is always the MikAura log level (info, warning, error), not the transfer outcome (success, no_file, failed).

Path 2: emit_ingestion_observability_log() (line 4472)
This is the outcome summary log -- one per retailer, emitted after the file processing loop finishes. It carries the actual transfer result (SUCCESS/NO_FILES/FAILED), file counts, failure reasons, and extra metadata like use_case, data_source_provider, data_source_bucket. It prints:

{"ingestion":{"evt":"transfer","client_id":"X","status":"SUCCESS","files_processed":3,"records_processed":142,"country":"US",...},"mikaura":{...}}
This function exists because MikAura's log_info() / log_error() alone cannot express:

The computed transfer status (SUCCESS vs NO_FILES vs PARTIAL vs FAILED)
The ingestion-specific fields (evt, use_case, data_source_provider, data_source_bucket)
The backward-compatible ingestion nested object (for older Datadog dashboards)
Why this is causing your Datadog widget problems
The problem is that these two paths collide in Datadog:

MikAura _transfer_info log	emit_ingestion_observability_log
files_processed location	flat (top-level)	nested (ingestion.files_processed)
status value	always info	the actual outcome (success, no_file, etc.)
Widget matches @files_processed:*?	Yes (wrong status)	No (field is nested)
So your widgets either see the wrong log (MikAura lifecycle with status: info) or see nothing (files_processed:0 doesn't exist at root).

Bottom line
emit_ingestion_observability_log exists to produce one structured outcome-summary log per retailer transfer with transfer-specific fields that MikAura's generic log_info() doesn't carry. The problem isn't that it exists -- it's that it wraps everything inside {"ingestion": {...}} instead of emitting those fields flat at the top level.

The plan we created addresses exactly this: promote the key fields to the JSON root so both the observability log and the flat Datadog widgets align. If you want me to implement that, switch to Agent mode and confirm the plan.
